snippet.textDisplay:
Watched a 90s documentary about the SR-71 a few years ago and something stood out from a story retold by a retired Blackbird pilot. He and his operator got a Missile warning so he pushed the throttle forward and just focused on flying the plane until the threat had passed but didn't realize how fast the plane was going by that point. Then he said something unusual, to the extent of "I was looking at mach numbers I'd never seen before." Now correct me if I'm wrong but wouldn't Mach 3+ be par for the course at that point? Why would he indicate that the speed was higher than the SR-71's official speed? More importantly, why didn't he just tell us the exact Mach numbers he was seeing?
Just something to think about.
snippet.textOriginal:
Watched a 90s documentary about the SR-71 a few years ago and something stood out from a story retold by a retired Blackbird pilot.  He and his operator got a Missile warning so he pushed the throttle forward and just focused on flying the plane until the threat had passed but didn't realize  how fast the plane was going by that point.  Then he said something unusual, to the extent of "I was looking at mach numbers I'd never seen before." Now correct me if I'm wrong but wouldn't Mach 3+ be par for the course at that point? Why would he indicate that the speed was higher than the SR-71's official speed? More importantly, why didn't he just tell us the exact Mach numbers he was seeing?  
Just something to think about.

snippet.textDisplay: Ah yes, those classic Pratt and Whitney J58s (JT11D-20)s were absolute beasts. They had to inject a substance called Triethylborane (TEB) into the fuel (called JP-7) due to not-volatile it was. Basically, you could throw a lit match into a puddle of the fuel, and it wouldn't ignite. So, TEB, which ignites on contact with air, would help in ignition. Now, why is this? Due to the high temperatures at such hugh speeds, normal jet fuel would've combusted within the fuel tanks.

snippet.textDisplay: The SR-71 was canceled due to its very dated cameras and technology, the expense of upgrading and even just operating it, and yes, even due to improved SAM tech. It's not 1960 anymore. Mach 3 and 80k feet won't keep you safe anymore, when you have SAMs designed to intercept ICBMs. Modern area defense missiles are 30-40ft long multistage rockets with top speeds over Mach 10 and max altitudes that are basically ''low orbit''. It would be extremely unwise to try to overfly something like that.

snippet.textDisplay: Fun Fact : By the mid-1980s, Swedish Viggen fighter pilots, using the predictable patterns of Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird routine flights over the Baltic Sea, had managed to achieve missile lock-on with radar on the SR-71 on numerous occasions. Despite heavy jamming from the SR-71, target illumination was maintained by feeding target location from ground-based radars to the fire-control computer in the Viggen. The most common site for the lock-on to occur was the thin stretch of international airspace between Öland and Gotland that the SR-71 used on the return flight. The Viggen is the only aircraft to get an acknowledged radar lock on the SR-71

snippet.textDisplay:
Skunkworks started with the A1 design and ended up getting the A12 design approved by the CIA. This is where it all started, and led to the later development of the YF12 and SR71 for the Air Force. The A12 was faster and had a higher service ceiling than the SR71.

The North Vietnam op was called Operation Black Shield and was flown by A12 pilots from the Agency.
